    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks that makes sense. i saw something about insects being a problem though. what kind of things usually clog them up and how bad is the impact on the flight instruments if it happens mid-flight?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the pesky little critters! Insects, yes, they can be quite the nuisance for the pitot tube. Think of them as tiny, flying specks of doom, determined to wreak havoc on your instruments. Flies, mosquitoes, even the occasional beetle can get sucked into the pitot tube, creating a blockage. This blockage prevents the tube from measuring the airspeed accurately, much like how a blocked garden hose would stop water from flowing.\n\nNow, if this happens mid-flight, it's like suddenly finding yourself in a thick fog with no visibility. The pilot can't trust the airspeed readings, which are crucial for maintaining control of the aircraft. It's a bit like trying to navigate through a maze blindfolded. The impact can be significant, potentially leading to unsafe flying conditions. That's why pilots are trained to handle such situations, and why regular maintenance checks are so important. It's all about staying one step ahead of the little critters, ensuring they don't turn your flight into a real-life horror story.",
      "source": "target",
